cise notation for large or small numbers</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about a numeric notation. For the musical notation, see <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_pitch_notation" title=3D"Scientific pi=
tch notation">Scientific pitch notation</a>.</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
"E notation" redirects here. For the series of preferred numbers, see <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_series_of_preferred_numbers" title=3D=
"E series of preferred numbers">E series</a>. For the food additive codes, =
see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_number" title=3D"E number">E=
 number</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">

</p><p><b>Scientific notation</b> is a way of expressing <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">numbers</a> that =
are too large or too small to be conveniently written in <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_separator" title=3D"Decimal separator">decim=
al form</a>, since to do so would require writing out an inconveniently lon=
g string of digits. It may be referred to as <b>scientific form</b> or <b>s=
tandard index form</b>, or <b>standard form</b> in the United Kingdom. This=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal" title=3D"Decimal">base t=
en</a> notation is commonly used by scientists, mathematicians, and enginee=
rs, in part because it can simplify certain <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Arithmetic" title=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic</a> operations. On <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_calculator" title=3D"Scie=
ntific calculator">scientific calculators</a>, it is usually known as "SCI"=
 display mode.
</p>
