<p>In scientific notation, nonzero numbers are written in the form=20
</p>
<div class=3D"block-indent" style=3D"padding-left: 1.5em;"><i>m</i> =C3=97 =
10<sup><i>n</i></sup></div>
<p>or <i>m</i> times ten raised to the power of <i>n</i>, where <i>n</i> is=
 an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">int=
eger</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient" tit=
le=3D"Coefficient">coefficient</a> <i>m</i> is a nonzero <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real number</a> (=
usually between 1 and 10 in absolute value, and nearly always written as a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal" title=3D"Decimal">termina=
ting decimal</a>). The integer <i>n</i> is called the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Exponent">expo=
nent</a> and the real number <i>m</i> is called the <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significand" title=3D"Significand">significand</a></i>=
 or <i>mantissa</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Calio_2017_1-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Cal=
io_2017-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> The term "mantissa" can be ambiguous where logarithms=
 are involved, because it is also the traditional name of the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_part" title=3D"Fractional part">frac=
tional part</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_loga=
rithm" title=3D"Common logarithm">common logarithm</a>.  If the number is n=
egative then a minus sign precedes <i>m</i>, as in ordinary decimal notatio=
n. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#Normaliz=
ed_notation">normalized notation</a>, the exponent is chosen so that the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_value" title=3D"Absolute va=
lue">absolute value</a> (modulus) of the significand <i>m</i> is at least 1=
 but less than 10.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_floating_point" tit=
le=3D"Decimal floating point">Decimal floating point</a> is a computer arit=
hmetic system closely related to scientific notation.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DScientific_notation&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit=
</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_lo=
garithms" title=3D"History of logarithms">History of logarithms</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#20th_century" title=3D=
"Exponentiation">Exponentiation =C2=A7&nbsp;20th century</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-center" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Slide_rule_example2_with_labels.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/8/8f/Slide_rule_example2_with_labels.svg/330px-Slide_rule_ex=
ample2_with_labels.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"70" =
class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"512" data-file-height=3D"119">=
</a><figcaption>Slide rules work by adding base-10 logarithms.</figcaption>=
</figure>
<p>For performing calculations with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Slide_rule" title=3D"Slide rule">slide rule</a>, standard form expressi=
on is required. Thus, the use of scientific notation increased as engineers=
 and educators used that tool. See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Slide_rule#History" title=3D"Slide rule">Slide rule#History</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Styles">Styles</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DScientific_notation&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Styles"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Normalized_notation">Normal=
ized notation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DScientific_notation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Normalized notation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normalized_number" t=
itle=3D"Normalized number">Normalized number</a></div>
<p>Any real number can be written in the form <span style=3D"white-space:no=
wrap"><i>m</i><span style=3D"margin-left:0.27em;margin-right:0.27em">=C3=97=
</span>10<span style=3D"display:none">^</span><sup><i>n</i></sup></span> in=
 many ways: for example, 350 can be written as <span class=3D"nowrap"><span=
 data-sort-value=3D"7002350000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>3.5<span style=3D"=
margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>2</sup></span>=
 or <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7002350000000000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>35<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=
=C3=97</span>10<sup>1</sup></span> or <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sor=
t-value=3D"7002350000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>350<span style=3D"margin-le=
ft:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>0</sup></span>.
</p><p>In <i>normalized</i> scientific notation (called "standard form" in =
the United Kingdom), the exponent <i>n</i> is chosen so that the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">abs=
olute value</a> of <i>m</i> remains at least one and less than ten (<span c=
lass=3D"nowrap">1 =E2=89=A4 |<span class=3D"nowrap" style=3D"padding-left:0=
.1em; padding-right:0.1em;"><i>m</i></span>| &lt; 10</span>). Thus 350 is w=
ritten as <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"70023500000000000=
00=E2=99=A0"></span>3.5<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15e=
m;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>2</sup></span>. This form allows easy comparison of=
 numbers: numbers with bigger exponents are (due to the normalization) larg=
er than those with smaller exponents, and subtraction of exponents gives an=
 estimate of the number of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orders_=
of_magnitude" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orders of magnitude">orders of=
 magnitude</a> separating the numbers.  It is also the form that is require=
d when using tables of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_loga=
rithm" title=3D"Common logarithm">common logarithms</a>. In normalized nota=
tion, the exponent <i>n</i> is negative for a number with absolute value be=
tween 0 and 1 (e.g. 0.5 is written as <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sor=
t-value=3D"6999500000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>5<span style=3D"margin-left=
:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span>).=
 The 10 and exponent are often omitted when the exponent is 0. For a series=
 of numbers that are to be added or subtracted (or otherwise compared), it =
can be convenient to use the same value of <i>m</i> for all elements of the=
 series.
</p><p>Normalized scientific form is the typical form of expression of larg=
e numbers in many fields, unless an unnormalized or differently normalized =
form, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering_notation=
" title=3D"Engineering notation">engineering notation</a>, is desired. Norm=
alized scientific notation is often called <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Exponentiation" title=3D"Exponentiation">exponential</a> notati=
on</b> =E2=80=93 although the latter term is more general and also applies =
when <i>m</i> is not restricted to the range 1 to 10 (as in engineering not=
ation for instance) and to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" =
title=3D"Radix">bases</a> other than 10 (for example, <span style=3D"white-=
space:nowrap">3.15<span style=3D"margin-left:0.27em;margin-right:0.27em">=
=C3=97</span>2<span style=3D"display:none">^</span><sup>20</sup></span>).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Engineering_notation">Engin=
eering notation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DScientific_notation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Engineering notation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering_notation=
" title=3D"Engineering notation">Engineering notation</a></div>
<p>Engineering notation (often named "ENG" on scientific calculators) diffe=
rs from normalized scientific notation in that the exponent <i>n</i> is res=
tricted to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_(mathematics)"=
 title=3D"Multiple (mathematics)">multiples</a> of 3. Consequently, the abs=
olute value of <i>m</i> is in the range 1 =E2=89=A4 |<i>m</i>| &lt; 1000, r=
ather than 1 =E2=89=A4 |<i>m</i>| &lt; 10. Though similar in concept, engin=
eering notation is rarely called scientific notation. Engineering notation =
allows the numbers to explicitly match their corresponding <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_prefixes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI pre=
fixes">SI prefixes</a>, which facilitates reading and oral communication. F=
or example, <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"699212500000000=
0000=E2=99=A0"></span>12.5<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.=
15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=929</sup>&nbsp;m</span> can be read as "t=
welve-point-five nanometres" and written as <span class=3D"nowrap"><span da=
ta-sort-value=3D"6992125000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>12.5&nbsp;nm</span>, =
while its scientific notation equivalent <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-=
sort-value=3D"6992125000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.25<span style=3D"margi=
n-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=928</sup>&nb=
sp;m</span> would likely be read out as "one-point-two-five times ten-to-th=
e-negative-eight metres".
</p>
