<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculator" title=3D"Calculator=
">Calculators</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_pro=
gram" title=3D"Computer program">computer programs</a> typically present ve=
ry large or small numbers using scientific notation, and some can be config=
ured to uniformly present all numbers that way. Because <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Superscript" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Superscri=
pt">superscript</a> exponents like 10<sup>7</sup> can be inconvenient to di=
splay or type, the letter "E" or "e" (for "exponent") is often used to repr=
esent "times ten raised to the power of", so that the notation <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><i>m</i>=E2=80=8AE=E2=80=8A<i>n</i></span> for a decimal signif=
icand <i>m</i> and integer exponent <i>n</i> means the same as <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><i>m</i> =C3=97 10<sup><i>n</i></sup></span>. For example <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avogadro_constant" title=3D"Avogadro co=
nstant"><span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7023602200000000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>6.022<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15e=
m;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>23</sup></span></a> is written as <code class=3D"mw=
-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">6.=
022E23</code> or <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-cont=
ent-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">6.022e23</code>, and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Planck_length" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Planck len=
gth"><span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6965160000000000000=E2=
=99=A0"></span>1.6<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=
=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9235</sup></span></a> is written as <code class=
=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"l=
tr">1.6E-35</code> or <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw=
-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">1.6e-35</code>. While common in comput=
er output, this abbreviated version of scientific notation is discouraged f=
or published documents by some style guides.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Edwards_200=
9_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scienti=
fic_notation#cite_note-Edwards_2009-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notati=
on#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Most popular programming languages =E2=80=93 including <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortran" title=3D"Fortran">Fortran</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title=3D"C (pro=
gramming language)">C</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B"=
 title=3D"C++">C++</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(pr=
ogramming_language)" title=3D"Python (programming language)">Python</a>, an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript" title=3D"JavaScript"=
>JavaScript</a> =E2=80=93 use this "E" notation, which comes from Fortran a=
nd was present in the first version released for the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM_704" title=3D"IBM 704">IBM 704</a> in 1956.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Fortran_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Fortran-4"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The E&nbsp;=
notation was already used by the developers of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/SHARE_Operating_System" title=3D"SHARE Operating System">SHARE=
 Operating System</a> (SOS) for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/IBM_709" title=3D"IBM 709">IBM 709</a> in 1958.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DiGri-=
King_1958_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Scientific_notation#cite_note-DiGri-King_1958-5"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Later versions=
 of Fortran (at least since <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FORTRA=
N_IV" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"FORTRAN IV">FORTRAN IV</a> as of 1961)=
 also use "D" to signify <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_pr=
ecision" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Double precision">double precision<=
/a> numbers in scientific notation,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-UH-Manoa_6-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation=
#cite_note-UH-Manoa-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and newer Fortran compilers use "Q" to si=
gnify <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadruple_precision" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quadruple precision">quadruple precision</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FortranQ_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-FortranQ-7"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MATLAB" title=3D"MATLAB">MATLAB</a> =
programming language supports the use of either "E" or "D".
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALGOL" title=3D"ALGOL">=
ALGOL 60</a> (1960) programming language uses a subscript ten "<sub>10</sub=
>" character instead of the letter "E", for example: <code class=3D"nowrap"=
>6.022<sub>10</sub>23</code>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Naur_1960_8-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_=
note-Naur_1960-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Savard_2005_9-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite=
_note-Savard_2005-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This presented a challenge for computer sys=
tems which did not provide such a character, so <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/ALGOL_W" title=3D"ALGOL W">ALGOL W</a> (1966) replaced the sy=
mbol by a single quote, e.g. <code>6.022'+23</code>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bau=
er-Becker-Graham_1968_10-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Bauer-Becker-Graham_1968-10"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> and some Soviet ALGOL variants allowed the use of the Cyrillic le=
tter "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yu_(Cyrillic)" title=3D"Yu (=
Cyrillic)">=D1=8E</a>", e.g. <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-=
text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">6.022=D1=8E+23</code><sup class=
=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references t=
o reliable sources. (December 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>.=
 Subsequently, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ALGOL_68" title=
=3D"ALGOL 68">ALGOL 68</a> programming language provided a choice of charac=
ters: <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" st=
yle=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">E</code>, <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lan=
g-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">e</code>, <code class=3D"mw-h=
ighlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">\</c=
ode>, <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" st=
yle=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">=E2=8A=A5</code>, or <code><sub>10</sub></code>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Algol_1973_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Algol_1973-11"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The ALGOL "<sub>10</sub>" character was included in the Soviet <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GOST_10859" title=3D"GOST 10859">GOST 10859</=
a> text encoding (1964), and was added to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Unicode" title=3D"Unicode">Unicode</a> 5.2 (2009) as <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span class=3D"monospaced">U+23E8</span> </span><span style=3D"fon=
t-size:125%;line-height:1em">=E2=8F=A8</span> <span style=3D"font-variant: =
small-caps; text-transform: lowercase; font-feature-settings: 'onum'">DECIM=
AL EXPONENT SYMBOL</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Unicode_12-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note=
-Unicode-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some programming languages use other symbols. For instance, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simula" title=3D"Simula">Simula</a> uses =
<code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D=
"" dir=3D"ltr">&amp;</code> (or <code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-la=
ng-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">&amp;&amp;</code> for <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_precision" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Double precision">long</a>), as in <code class=3D"nowrap mw-highli=
ght mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">6.022&amp=
;23</code>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SIMULA_1986_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-SIMULA_198=
6-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematica" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mathematica">Mathematica</a> supports the short=
hand notation <code class=3D"nowrap mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-=
content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">6.022*^23</code> (reserving the letter =
<code class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D=
"" dir=3D"ltr">E</code> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E_=
(mathematical_constant)" title=3D"E (mathematical constant)">mathematical c=
onstant <i>e</i></a>).
</p><p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Decapower"></span><span class=3D"anchor=
" id=3D"D_notation"></span>
</p>
