iki/Avogadro_constant" title=3D"Avogadro constant">Avogadro constant</a> to=
 three significant figures in E notation</figcaption></figure>
<p>The first <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pocket_calculator" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pocket calculator">pocket calculators</a> supp=
orting scientific notation appeared in 1972.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TI_1973_SR-=
10_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scien=
tific_notation#cite_note-TI_1973_SR-10-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To enter numbers in =
scientific notation calculators include a button labeled "EXP" or "=C3=9710=
<sup><i>x</i></sup>", among other variants. The displays of pocket calculat=
ors of the 1970s did not display an explicit symbol between significand and=
 exponent; instead, one or more digits were left blank (e.g. <code>6.022 23=
</code>, as seen in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP-25" tit=
le=3D"HP-25">HP-25</a>), or a pair of smaller and slightly raised digits we=
re reserved for the exponent (e.g. <code>6.022 <sup>23</sup></code>, as see=
n in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_International" =
title=3D"Commodore International">Commodore PR100</a>). In 1976, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hewlett-Packard" title=3D"Hewlett-Packard">H=
ewlett-Packard</a> calculator user Jim Davidson coined the term <i>decapowe=
r</i> for the scientific-notation exponent to distinguish it from "normal" =
exponents, and suggested the letter "D" as a separator between significand =
and exponent in typewritten numbers (for example, <code class=3D"mw-highlig=
ht mw-highlight-lang-text mw-content-ltr" style=3D"" dir=3D"ltr">6.022D23</=
code>); these gained some currency in the programmable calculator user comm=
unity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Decapower_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Decapower-15"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The letters "E" or "D" were used as a scientific-notation separato=
r by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharp_Corporation" title=3D"S=
harp Corporation">Sharp</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pocket=
_computer" title=3D"Pocket computer">pocket computers</a> released between =
1987 and 1995, "E" used for 10-digit numbers and "D" used for 20-digit doub=
le-precision numbers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sharp_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Sharp-=
16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Texas_Instrume=
nts" title=3D"Texas Instruments">Texas Instruments</a> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-83_series" title=3D"TI-83 series">TI-83</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI-84_Plus_series" title=3D"TI-84 Plu=
s series">TI-84</a> series of calculators (1996=E2=80=93present) use a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_caps" title=3D"Small caps">small=
 capital</a> <code><small>E</small></code> for the separator.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-TI-83_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-TI-83-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1962, Ronald O. Whitaker of Rowco Engineering Co. proposed a powe=
r-of-ten system nomenclature where the exponent would be circled, e.g. 6.02=
2&nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;10<sup>3</sup> would be written as "6.022=E2=91=A2".<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Whitaker_1962_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Whitaker_1962-18"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Significant_figures">Signif=
icant figures</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DScientific_notation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Significant figures"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures"=
 title=3D"Significant figures">Significant figures</a></div>
<p>A significant figure is a digit in a number that adds to its precision. =
This includes all nonzero numbers, zeroes between significant digits, and z=
eroes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significant_figures#Identify=
ing_significant_digits" title=3D"Significant figures">indicated to be signi=
ficant</a>. Leading and trailing zeroes are not significant digits, because=
 they exist only to show the scale of the number. Unfortunately, this leads=
 to ambiguity. The number <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7=
006123040000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">230=
</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">400</span></span> is usually read=
 to have five significant figures: 1, 2, 3, 0, and 4, the final two zeroes =
serving only as placeholders and adding no precision. The same number, howe=
ver, would be used if the last two digits were also measured precisely and =
found to equal 0 =E2=80=93 seven significant figures.
</p><p>When a number is converted into normalized scientific notation, it i=
s scaled down to a number between 1 and 10. All of the significant digits r=
emain, but the placeholding zeroes are no longer required. Thus <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7006123040000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1=
<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">230</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25=
em;">400</span></span> would become <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-=
value=3D"7006123040000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.2304<span style=3D"margin-l=
eft:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>6</sup></span> if it h=
ad five significant digits. If the number were known to six or seven signif=
icant figures, it would be shown as <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-=
value=3D"7006123040000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.230<span style=3D"margin-le=
ft:.25em;">40</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;"=
>=C3=97</span>10<sup>6</sup></span> or <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-so=
rt-value=3D"7006123040000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1.230<span style=3D"margin=
-left:.25em;">400</span><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15=
em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>6</sup></span>. Thus, an additional advantage of s=
cientific notation is that the number of significant figures is unambiguous=
.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Estimated_final_digits">Est=
imated final digits</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DScientific_notation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edi=
t section: Estimated final digits"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>It is customary in scientific measurement to record all the definitely k=
nown digits from the measurement and to estimate at least one additional di=
git if there is any information at all available on its value. The resultin=
g number contains more information than it would without the extra digit, w=
hich may be considered a significant digit because it conveys some informat=
ion leading to greater precision in measurements and in aggregations of mea=
surements (adding them or multiplying them together).
</p><p>More detailed information about the precision of a value written in =
scientific notation can be conveyed through additional notation. For instan=
ce, the accepted value of the mass of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Proton" title=3D"Proton">proton</a> can be expressed as <span class=
=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6973167262192595000=E2=99=A0"></span>1=
.672<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">621</span><span style=3D"margin-left=
:.25em;">925</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">95</span>(52)<span st=
yle=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=
=9227</sup>&nbsp;kg</span>, which is shorthand for <span class=3D"nowrap"><=
span data-sort-value=3D"6973167262192595000=E2=99=A0"></span>(1.672<span st=
yle=3D"margin-left:.25em;">621</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">925=
</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">95</span><span style=3D"margin-le=
ft:0.225em;margin-right:0.225em;">=C2=B1</span>0.000<span style=3D"margin-l=
eft:.25em;">000</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">000</span><span st=
yle=3D"margin-left:.25em;">52</span>)<span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;marg=
in-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=E2=88=9227</sup>&nbsp;kg</span>. How=
ever, it is unclear whether an error expressed in this way (<span class=3D"=
nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6963520000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>5.2<s=
pan style=3D"margin-left:0.25em;margin-right:0.15em;">=C3=97</span>10<sup>=
=E2=88=9237</sup></span> in this case) is the maximum possible error, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_error" title=3D"Standard error=
">standard error</a>, or some other <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Confidence_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence interval</a=
>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use_of_spaces">Use of space=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DScientific=
_notation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Use of =
spaces"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>In normalized scientific notation, in E notation, and in engineering not=
ation, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Space_(punctuation)" ti=
tle=3D"Space (punctuation)">space</a> (which in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Typesetting" title=3D"Typesetting">typesetting</a> may be rep=
resented by a normal width space or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Thin_space" title=3D"Thin space">thin space</a>) that is allowed <i>onl=
y</i> before and after "=C3=97" or in front of "E" is sometimes omitted, th=
ough it is less common to do so before the alphabetical character.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Samples_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Samples-19"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
