</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_bases">Other bases <s=
pan class=3D"anchor" id=3D"B_notation"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"=
H_notation"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"O_notation"></span><span cl=
ass=3D"anchor" id=3D"C_notation"></span><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"P_nota=
tion"></span></h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DScientific_notation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Other bases"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>While base ten is normally used for scientific notation, powers of other=
 bases can be used too,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TI_1974_SR-22_25-0" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_n=
ote-TI_1974_SR-22-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> base 2 being the next most commonly used =
one.
</p><p>For example, in base-2 scientific notation, the number 1001<sub>b</s=
ub> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numeral_system" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary numeral system">binary</a> (=3D9<sub>d</s=
ub>) is written as <span class=3D"nowrap">1.001<sub>b</sub> =C3=97 2<sub>d<=
/sub><sup>11<sub>b</sub></sup></span> or <span class=3D"nowrap">1.001<sub>b=
</sub> =C3=97 10<sub>b</sub><sup>11<sub>b</sub></sup></span> using binary n=
umbers (or shorter <span class=3D"nowrap">1.001 =C3=97 10<sup>11</sup></spa=
n> if binary context is obvious).<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Temp=
late-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><=
span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (March 2024)=
">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> In E notation, this is written as <=
span class=3D"nowrap">1.001<sub>b</sub>E11<sub>b</sub></span> (or shorter: =
1.001E11) with the letter "E" now standing for "times two (10<sub>b</sub>) =
to the power" here. In order to better distinguish this base-2 exponent fro=
m a base-10 exponent, a base-2 exponent is sometimes also indicated by usin=
g the letter "B" instead of "E",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-Lib_26-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation=
#cite_note-HP16C-Lib-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a shorthand notation originally propos=
ed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBruce_Alan_Ma=
rtin&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Bruce Alan M=
artin (page does not exist)">Bruce Alan Martin</a> of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brookhaven_National_Laboratory" title=3D"Brookhaven Nat=
ional Laboratory">Brookhaven National Laboratory</a> in 1968,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Martin_1968_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Martin_1968-27"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> as in <=
span class=3D"nowrap">1.001<sub>b</sub>B11<sub>b</sub></span> (or shorter: =
1.001B11). For comparison, the same number in <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Decimal_representation" title=3D"Decimal representation">decima=
l representation</a>: <span class=3D"nowrap">1.125 =C3=97 2<sup>3</sup></sp=
an> (using decimal representation), or 1.125B3 (still using decimal represe=
ntation). Some calculators use a mixed representation for binary floating p=
oint numbers, where the exponent is displayed as decimal number even in bin=
ary mode, so the above becomes <span class=3D"nowrap">1.001<sub>b</sub> =C3=
=97 10<sub>b</sub><sup>3<sub>d</sub></sup></span> or shorter 1.001B3.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-Lib_26-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Lib-26"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>This is closely related to the base-2 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Floating-point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Floating-point">f=
loating-point</a> representation commonly used in computer arithmetic, and =
the usage of IEC <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_prefixes" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Binary prefixes">binary prefixes</a> (e.g. 1=
B10 for 1=C3=972<sup>10</sup> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kib=
i-" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kibi-">kibi</a>), 1B20 for 1=C3=972<sup>=
20</sup> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mebi-" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Mebi-">mebi</a>), 1B30 for 1=C3=972<sup>30</sup> (<a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gibi-" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gibi-">=
gibi</a>), 1B40 for 1=C3=972<sup>40</sup> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Tebi-" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tebi-">tebi</a>)).
</p><p>Similar to "B" (or "b"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-Add_28-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite=
_note-HP16C-Add-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>), the letters "H"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-=
Lib_26-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scie=
ntific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Lib-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (or "h"<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-HP16C-Add_28-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Add-28"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) and "O"<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-Lib_26-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Lib-26"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (o=
r "o",<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-Add_28-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Add-28"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> or "C"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HP16C-Lib_26-4" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Li=
b-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>) are sometimes also used to indicate <i>times 16 or 8 to =
the power</i> as in 1.25 =3D <span class=3D"nowrap">1.40<sub>h</sub> =C3=97=
 10<sub>h</sub><sup>0<sub>h</sub></sup></span> =3D 1.40H0 =3D 1.40h0, or 98=
000 =3D <span class=3D"nowrap">2.7732<sub>o</sub> =C3=97 10<sub>o</sub><sup=
>5<sub>o</sub></sup></span> =3D 2.7732o5 =3D 2.7732C5.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-H=
P16C-Lib_26-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Scientific_notation#cite_note-HP16C-Lib-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another similar convention to denote base-2 exponents is using a let=
ter "P" (or "p", for "power"). In this notation the significand is always m=
eant to be hexadecimal, whereas the exponent is always meant to be decimal.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rationale_2003_C_29-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Rationale_2003_C=
-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> This notation can be produced by implementations of the <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printf" title=3D"Printf">printf</=
a></i> family of functions following the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/C99" title=3D"C99">C99</a> specification and (<a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_Unix_Specification" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Single Unix Specification">Single Unix Specification</a>) <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_Std_1003.1" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"IEEE Std 1003.1">IEEE Std 1003.1</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/POSIX" title=3D"POSIX">POSIX</a> standard, when using the <i>%a</i> or =
<i>%A</i> conversion specifiers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rationale_2003_C_29-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_not=
ation#cite_note-Rationale_2003_C-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-printf_=
2013_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sci=
entific_notation#cite_note-printf_2013-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-B=
eebe_2017_Hex_31-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Beebe_2017_Hex-31"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Starting=
 with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B11" title=3D"C++11">C=
++11</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B" title=3D"C++">C=
++</a> I/O functions could parse and print the P notation as well. Meanwhil=
e, the notation has been fully adopted by the language standard since <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B17" title=3D"C++17">C++17</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-C++17_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-C++17-32"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apple_Inc." title=3D"Apple Inc.">Apple</a=
>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swift_(programming_language)" =
title=3D"Swift (programming language)">Swift</a> supports it as well.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Swift_2017_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation#cite_note-Swift_2017-33"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 It is also required by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IEEE_7=
54-2008" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"IEEE 754-2008">IEEE 754-2008</a> bi=
nary floating-point standard. Example: 1.3DEp42 represents <span class=3D"n=
owrap">1.3DE<sub>h</sub> =C3=97 2<sup>42</sup></span>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineering_notation" title=
=3D"Engineering notation">Engineering notation</a> can be viewed as a base-=
1000 scientific notation.
</p>
